<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>DDB0176</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">David </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Whitton</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Head of Highways, Capital Development and Waste,</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> on behalf of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Devon County Council</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> – Written evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Clauses 12-18 and Schedule 6: Public Rights of Way</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:6.29pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Devon County Council (DCC) is broadly supportive of the measures contained in the draft Deregulation Bill regarding public rights of way. These measures aim to implement some of the key recommendations published by the Stakeholder Working Group in the 2010 Stepping Forward report, and a number of proposals introduced by Defra in May 2012 as part of a wider package of improvements to reduce the amount of regulation and speed up legislative processes for rights of way. Those recommendations and proposals that require primary legislation now form clauses in the draft Deregulation Bill.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:6.29pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The changes to primary legislation will require secondary legislation and guidance. It is anticipated that statutory instruments will also be used to implement other changes, such as implementing the cut-off date for adding historic routes to the Definitive Map and Statement, which is the basis of the Stakeholder Working Group’s proposals, and the right to apply for public path orders. As draft </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">egulations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have not yet been published it is difficult to assess the full implications of the clauses contained in the draft Deregulation Bill. They appear to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">reduce some </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">areas of bureaucracy whilst introducing new duties for the authority in other areas.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:6.29pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In response to the questions raised by the Joint Committee’s Call for Evidence, DCC’s comments largely address questions 3 and 4. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:6.29pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We would like to note our support of the following changes, subject to further details published in draft regulations and guidance.</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Clause 12: Recorded rights of way: additional protection</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Clause</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">13: Unrecorded rights of way: protection from extinguishment</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Clause 15: Application by owners etc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for public path orders</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Clause 17: Applications for certain order under Highways Act 1980: cost recovery</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Schedule 6, paragraph 5: Modifications of definitive map and statement by consent</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Schedule 6, paragraph 6 (3)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">: Preliminary assessment and notice of applications.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 57.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:6.29pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DCC is concerned by the proposals included at:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Schedule 6, paragraph 6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(4): </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Failure by authority to conduct preliminary assessment and Failure by authority to determine application.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:6.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We make further comments in response to questions 3 and 4 concerning:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Clause 16: Extension of powers to authorise erection of stiles</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Schedule 6, Paragraph 2: Removal of “reasonably alleged to subsist”</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Schedule 6, paragraph 6 (2) (3): Provision of documentary evidence</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.07pt; padding-left:3.63pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Schedule 6, paragraphs 7 and 9: Ending of requirement to serve notice in a local newspaper.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In response to question 15, we consider that the provision included at Schedule 6, paragraph 5 should be extended to modifications proposed by a surveying authority, under Schedule 15 of the Wildlife Act 1981. There is also one additional reform to rights of way legislation which we think would be of merit for inclusion, namely</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A new category for cycle ways to be recorded on the Definitive Map and Statement.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Clause 12: Recorded rights of way: additional protection</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:6.29pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Devon County Council (DCC) supports the inclusion of a provision to give extra protection to already-recorded public rights of way after the 2026 cut-off date. This would also appear to correct an unfair contradiction under the existing legislation whereby, after the cut-off date, routes could not be added to the Definitive Map and Statement, or upgraded, on the basis of pre-1949 evidence but already-recorded public rights could be downgraded or deleted.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:6.29pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It would also appear to achieve the purpose of reducing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">regulatory burden on surveying authorities that aris</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">es</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> from having to consider in detail applications for modifications to the Definitive Map and Statement which require an investigation of historical evidence.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:6.29pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The wording of the new section 55A(1) to be inserted into the Countryside and Rights of Way Act 2000</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> as included in the draft Bill</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> could be open to interpretation. It is not clear whether ‘make a modification’ includes confirmation of modification orders made before the cut-off date. This requires clarification.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Clause 13</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">: Unrecorded rights of way: protection from extinguishment</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Subject to further regulations concerning the detail of this provision, DCC also welcomes the inclusion of this clause which will enable surveying authorities to protect certain unrecorded rights of way from extinguishment during a post cut-off date period. This will allow authorities to wait until after the cut-off date to assess what research has already been carried out by individuals or other organisations and avoid potential duplication of work, thereby reducing the administrative burden on surveying authorities.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is proposed that regulations will specify the timescale for determining ‘designated’ routes and the procedure which will apply in the event that an authority fails to make a determination within that time period. Draft regulations have not yet been published. It is therefore difficult to assess the implications of this provision. To avoid increasing the regulatory burden on authorities, the timescale will need to be sufficient to allow authorities to determine these designated routes together with a potential backlog of applications made immediately prior to the cut-off date.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> We await publication of draft Regulations concerning the details of the procedure. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Clause 15</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">: Applications by owners etc. for public path orders</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Implementing and extending the right to apply provisions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for public path orders</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to other, specified, types of land achieves a fairer system for landowners. It will however increase the regulatory and administrative burden on local authorities. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DCC supports the making of diversion orders which are in the interests of users and/or landowners, provided that they meet the necessary legal tests. Currently applications are dealt with on a case-by-case basis, with the timescale largely dependent o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> staff resources and workload. The right to apply provisions will remove the authority’s freedom to deal with applications in the context of local priorities and policies. As no draft regulations have been published it is difficult to assess the full impact. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Clause 16</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">: Extension of powers to authorise erection of stiles etc.</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DCC supports the extension of powers to authorise structures on byways as this will address a current imbalance. Local authorities will still have discretion in giving authorisation, and must be satisfied that it is expedient to do so, thereby also safeguarding the needs of users.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DCC also welcomes the inclusion of a provision to enable surveying authorities to modify the Definitive Map and Statement to reflect duly authorised structures, using the same procedure as for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">L</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">egal Event Modification Orders.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Clause 17</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">: Applications for certain orders under Highways Act 1980: cost recovery</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DCC welcomes the inclusion of a provision to amend existing legislation, as introduced by the CROW Act, to enable authorities to recover their full costs associated with public path orders made under the right to apply</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> provisions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, subject to the Secretary of State making the necessary regulations. This will reduce the financial burden on an authority, which could arise if the centrally prescribed limit, as specified in the current legislation, does not enable it to recover all of its costs. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Schedule 6, Paragraph 2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">: Removal of “reasonably alleged to subsist”</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DCC does not anticipate any reduction in the overall burden on the authority with the removal of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> words ‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">reasonably alleged to subsist</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’ from Section 53(3)(c)(i), thus raising the threshold at which an authority is required to make an order to add a route to the Definitive Map and Statement. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The focus of the workload is likely to be moved to a different stage in the process. For example, the application of a more robust test for making an order is likely to result in a more lengthy determination process. It may also result in fewer orders being made, but there is also a risk that more of the authority’s decisions will be submitted to the Secretary of State on appeal.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In terms of fairness for individuals, fewer cases will have the opportunity of being </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">fully </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">scrutinised in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> public </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">forum</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, i.e. at Public Inquiry. In Devon, the majority of orders made on the basis of the reasonabl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> allege</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> test and which have been opposed have subsequently been confirmed by the Secretary of State.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Schedule 6, Paragraph </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5: Modification by consent</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DCC supports m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">odification of the definitive map and statement by consent, where landowners accept that a route should be added and consent to the proposal, in some cases subject to agreed modifications.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">his clause </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pragmatic approach to recording historic routes, whilst taking needs of modern land use into consideration. It would appear however, that this provision would only apply to applications made under schedule 14 of the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981, not for modifications sought by the authority under its powers under schedule 15. In Devon for example, the County Council fulfils its statutory duty to keep the Definitive Map and Statement under continuous review by carrying out a review on a parish-by-parish basis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> under Schedule 15</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Similarly, it is not clear whether the provisions for modification consent orders will apply to routes designated by surveying authorities during the post cut-off date period (Clause 12). It would be sensible if modification consent orders could be considered in these cases.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The modification consent order process does however introduce another short time period, within which the authority must make the order, placing an additional burden on the authority. Any benefits of this provision, for landowners, users and surveying authorities, will be dependent on authorities having the necessary resources to carry out investigations and negotiations within the specified time period. If the surveying authority is unable to do so, it will still be required to determine the application as usual, with or without the landowner’s consent. We consider that for this clause to be more effective, a longer time period is required, and would suggest twelve months is more achievable. This is also consistent with the schedule 14 application process.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Schedule 6, paragraph 6(2)(3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">)</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Under this provision a surveying authority would be able to inform a potential applicant that they have access to documentary evidence and do not require a copy to be submitted with the application. Where documents are easily accessible to the authority, for example held on-site or available electronically, it would seem sensible that a potential applicant is not required to provide copies. This will reduce the burden on individuals and voluntary organisations and DCC supports the clause. It is important that authorities retain the right to request copies, where for example documents are held off-site in local or national records offices, and obtaining copies would place an additional burden on an authority’s resources.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Schedule 6, paragraph 6(3)</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The introduction of a new preliminary assessment for applications made under schedule 14 of the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">should have the intended purpose of reducing the burden on surveying authorities and landowners, of investigating and determining applications that are spurious or poorly founded. The measure will however introduce a new timescale in which authorities will be required to carry out the preliminary assessment. The impact of this will be dependent on resources. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We therefore consider </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that this assessment should be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">primarily </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a desk-based exercise, with the evidence submitted with the application considered at face value to avoid increasing the burden on surveying authorities. DCC therefore welcomes the clause in principle, subject to further regulations for detailing the procedure. Authority decisions risk judicial review</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> therefore clear guidelines will be necessary to ensure consistency and transparency.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DCC is concerned that the burden of serving notice of applications, which pass the preliminary assessment, will be shifted from the applicant to the surveying authority. It would appear that authorities will also be expected to ascertain the identities of landowners and occupiers (sub-paragraph 5), with resulting cost implications for authorities, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for example Land Registry fees.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Draft regulations and guidance has not yet been published so it is difficult to fully assess the implications. For example, would the preliminary assessment apply retrospectively to outstanding applications? If so, there would need to be a sufficient transitional period to enable authorities to assess the backlog of outstanding applications. If the preliminary assessment is not retrospective it risks a two-tier system of applications.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Schedule 6, paragraph 6(4)</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This clause introduces a right of appeal to Magistrates Court, in respect of failure to conduct a preliminary assessment or failure to determine an application. It is intended to replace the current right of appeal to the Secretary of State, which is considered largely ineffective and results in a lengthy period of uncertainty for those involved. It is not clear however how this measure will produce a reduction in burden or make the system more effective. DCC has no evidence to support this view. We have serious concerns with this measure, which we consider will simply shift the administrative burden to the courts system. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">At present schedule 14 appeals are dealt with by written representations. Attending court hearings in person, possibly twice, will increase the burden on local authorities, applicants and landowners, with additional cost implications for all parties. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We would query whether the number of cases and potential impact on Magistrates Courts, has been taken into account. We are also concerned that Magistrates Courts will not have sufficient understanding of relevant policies and procedures when considering authorities failure to comply with specified timescales. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Application to Magistrates Court is a disproportionate measure for what is essentially an administrative process. It is also inconsistent with the treatment for applications for public path orders which, under the right to apply provisions, will go to the Secretary of State on appeal.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Further, in DCC’s experience the current process of appeals to the Secretary of State, through the Planning Inspectorate, is working effectively.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DCC does however support, in terms of fairness, the extension of a right of appeal to landowners affected by applications.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">here an authority decides not to make an order</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in respect of a schedule 14 application</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">under current legislation an applicant may appeal to the Secretary of State. If the Secretary of State subsequently directs the authority to make an order, and the order is objected to, the case may end up being sent back to the Secretary of State for a second time as an opposed order. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DCC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">therefore </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">welcomes the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">proposed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">measures to streamline the process and ensure that a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">case is referred to the Secretary of State only once, provided that there is adequate opportunity for evidence to be heard in a public forum. It could introduce additional costs earlier in the process however</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> as all parties will be advised to make their full case prior to determination of the schedule 14 appeal.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Clear guidance will be required.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We also support the introduction of a power to discount irrelevant grounds of appeal. Clear guidelines will be required to ensure consistency and avoid the risk of complaints or judicial review.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Schedule 6, paragraphs 7 and 9</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DCC welcomes the proposal to end the requirement to serve notice of modification and public path orders in a local newspaper. We consider the circulation of newspapers is small and is no longer the best media for publication of local orders. Ending this requirement will produce significant cost savings for authorities, with the average cost for two notices in Devon being approximately £600. This cost saving will also be passed on to applicants for public path orders.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Local authorities should however consider what other publicity would be required to ensure fair and reasonable access to information, for example parish newsletters or notice boards.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Other changes which should have been included (Question 15)</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There has been significant investment in Devon for the creation and promotion of cycle ways and multi-use routes. Most recently plans to improve cycling to and across Dartmoor were backed with a £4.4 million grant from the Government. DCC’s policy is to promote multi-use routes where at all possible. In some cases however, it is not always feasible or suitable to record such routes as bridleways. Similarly, some landowners may be willing to dedicate public rights for use on foot and bicycle, but not horses. There is currently no mechanism for cycle ways to be recorded on the Definitive Map and Statement.  We therefore consider that the current reforms would be an opportunity to amend legislation to introduce a new category of cycle ways on the Definitive Map and Statement, to offer them the same protection as public rights of way.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">6</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>